\begin_layout Subsection
Classical Probability Spaces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The conventional definition of a probability space builds upon the field
 of real numbers.
 In more detail, a probability space consists of a 
\emph on
sample space
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

, a space of 
\emph on
events
\emph default

\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\events$
\end_inset

, and a 
\emph on
probability measure
\emph default

\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\pmeas$
\end_inset

 mapping events in 
\begin_inset Formula $\events$
\end_inset

 to the real interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 We will only consider 
\emph on
finite
\emph default
 sets of events and restrict our attention to non-empty finite sets 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 as the sample space.
 The space of events 
\begin_inset Formula $\events$
\end_inset

 includes every possible subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

: it is the powerset
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $2^{\Omega}=\set{E}{E\subseteq\Omega}$
\end_inset

.
 For future reference, we emphasize that events are the primary notion of
 interest and that the sample space is a convenient artifact that allows
 us to treat events as sets obeying the laws of Boolean algebra
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Boole1948,Redhead1987-REDINA,Griffiths2003"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{definition}
\end_layout

\end_inset

[Probability Measure]
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "def:ClassicalProbabilitySpace"

\end_inset

 Given the set of events 
\begin_inset Formula $\events$
\end_inset

, a 
\emph on
probability measure
\emph default
 is a function 
\begin_inset Formula $\pmeas:\events\rightarrow[0,1]$
\end_inset

 such that: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\pmeas(\emptyset)=0$
\end_inset

, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\pmeas(\Omega)=1$
\end_inset

, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
for every event 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\pmeas\left(\Omega\backslash E\right)=1-\pmeas\left(E\right)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega\backslash E$
\end_inset

 is the complement event of 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

, and 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
for every collection 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ E_{i}\right\} _{i=1}^{N}$
\end_inset

 of pairwise disjoint events, 
\begin_inset Formula $\pmeas\left(\bigcup_{i=1}^{N}E_{i}\right)=\sum_{i=1}^{N}\pmeas(E_{i})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{definition}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 There is some redundancy in the definition that will be useful when moving
 to quantum probability spaces.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

[Two-coins experiment]
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "ex1"

\end_inset

 Consider an experiment that tosses two coins.
 We have four possible outcomes that constitute the sample space 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega=\{HH,HT,TH,TT\}$
\end_inset

.
 There are 16 total events including the event 
\begin_inset Formula $\{HH,HT\}$
\end_inset

 that the first coin lands heads up, the event 
\begin_inset Formula $\{HT,TH\}$
\end_inset

 that the two coins land on opposite sides, and the event 
\begin_inset Formula $\{HT,TH,TT\}$
\end_inset

 that at least one coin lands tails up.
 Here is a possible probability measure for these events: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{c@{\qquad\qquad}c}
\begin{array}{rcl}
\pmeas(\emptyset) & = & 0\\
\pmeas(\{HH\}) & = & 1/3\\
\pmeas(\{HT\}) & = & 0\\
\pmeas(\{TH\}) & = & 2/3\\
\pmeas(\{TT\}) & = & 0\\
\pmeas(\{HH,HT\}) & = & 1/3\\
\pmeas(\{HH,TH\}) & = & 1\\
\pmeas(\{HH,TT\}) & = & 1/3
\end{array} & \begin{array}{rcl}
\pmeas(\{HT,TH\}) & = & 2/3\\
\pmeas(\{HT,TT\}) & = & 0\\
\pmeas(\{TH,TT\}) & = & 2/3\\
\pmeas(\{HH,HT,TH\}) & = & 1\\
\pmeas(\{HH,HT,TT\}) & = & 1/3\\
\pmeas(\{HH,TH,TT\}) & = & 1\\
\pmeas(\{HT,TH,TT\}) & = & 2/3\\
\pmeas(\{HH,HT,TH,TT\}) & = & 1
\end{array}\end{array}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
It is useful to think that this probability measure is completely determined
 by the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

reality
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of the two coins in question and their characteristics, in the sense that
 each pair of coins induces a measure, and each measure must correspond
 to some pair of coins.
 The measure above would be induced by two particular coins such that the
 first coin is twice as likely to land tails up than heads up and the second
 coin is double-headed.
 In a strict computational or experimental setting, one should question
 the reliance of the definition of probability space on the uncountable
 and uncomputable real interval
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Turing_1937,Ziegler2007,weihrauch2012computable"

\end_inset

.
 This interval includes numbers like 
\begin_inset Formula $0.h_{1}h_{2}h_{3}\ldots$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{i}$
\end_inset

 is 1 or 0 depending on whether Turing machine 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathit{TM}_{i}$
\end_inset

 halts or not.
 Such numbers cannot be computed.
 This interval also includes numbers like 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\pi}{4}$
\end_inset

 which can only be computed with increasingly large resources as the precision
 increases.
 Therefore, in a resource-aware computational or experimental setting, it
 is more appropriate to consider probability measures that map events to
 a set of elements computable with a fixed set of resources.
 We expand on this observation in the next section and then recall its formaliza
tion using interval-valued probability measures
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Weichselberger2000,JamisonLodwick2004"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

